review_blob: very well balanced. bottle. pours black with copper highlights. very thin to no head.  aroma is very faint smells mostly of chocolate and smoke. starts with a tingle as to suggest alot of carbonation but the head says otherwise. but urgently turns to a silky chocolate  and then a smoky hop flavor that lasts. after the bottle i noticed my mouth was really dry. i dont know what that means so i wrote it. overall i think it would make a great day to day beer.

bottle. pours a dark redish brown. biege head about two inches of it.  lasting with a beautiful lacing. smells predominitly caramel with kind of a vinegar sent. taste is unbalanced. taste starts with caramel and sharply turns to bitter hoppy taste. the idea of a caramel porter is really inticing but i think it could be better.
the one thing that makes this stout stand out is the penetrating alcohol taste. way to much guys.

the best beer i have had yet. pours a stunning black. held up to the light you cant see through it.  a lucios wet sand head. smells of chocolate and my grandpas wood shop. when you taste it you will notice that its perfectly balanced. starts with a toasty chocolated then the oak comes through. the only think i thought that was wrong with it is that the alcohol is not hidden to well. overall it sets a high standard for aged impy stouts.
beer_name: Great Divide Yeti Imperial Stout - Oak Aged

review_blob: pours black with red highlights. had a short lastin carmel colored head. about an inch thinck. smells of chocolate. has a bitter start. then the smoke and roast really piece through. has a slight chocolate finish.  it really reminds me of a porter for its faint chocolate taste good brew!!

pours an excelllent oil color with almost a mississippi red earth head. smells like carmel at first but upon further sniffing i catch the deep chocolate smell. tastes the same altough the chocolate may be a little overpowering. nice biter finish all and all a great impy. to my standard

pours beautiful burgundy with a deep bright red. thin pale head. smeels of vannila and nothing more. really sweet start alot of vinnila with a faint bitterness to finish. another extremely smooth beer with very little carbonation. i think its a good gateway brew.

pours black with amber tint. a very thin carmel color head. smells hint of chocolate and roasted malts. tastes the same with a long bitter aftertaste. how ever it goes down extemly smooth good for a hot day.

for my first rating i wanted it to be something special so i held out until shannon ireland. It pourd out smooth dark. smelled roasty.  tasty kind of earthy. it wasnt to heavy on the palate. all in all it was a good beer that i would reccomend to anyone
